[1] Case updates
- Thu 28 Feb 2019. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=ec0e947de0

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 27 Feb 2019:
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 885, of which 820 are confirmed and 65 are probable. In total, there have been 555 deaths (490 of confirmed and 65 of probable cases);
- 27 suspected cases under investigation;
- 6 new confirmed cases, including 5 in Katwa and 1 in Kalunguta. The new case confirmed in Kalunguta is a known contact of a confirmed case of Katwa who had refused follow-up and vaccination;
- 2 new deaths of confirmed cases, including 1 in Katwa and 1 in Kalunguta (all community deaths);
- 1 recovery released from the Beni ETC.

**Database clean-up in progress: revision of the database of those who have recovered. We will start sharing the number of recoveries as soon as the revision is complete.**

News of the response
Minister's visit to Butembo
---------------------------
- On Thu 28 Feb 2019, the minister of health, Dr Oly Ilunga Kalenga, accompanied by the representative of the WHO in the DRC, went to Butembo to inquire about the situation on the ground following the 2 arson [events] that destroyed Ebola treatment centers [ETCs] in Katwa and Butembo.
- These 2 incidents greatly disrupted the response teams. For several days, these teams have been the target of attacks and threats that have significantly slowed down the response activities, particularly the follow-up of contacts, the investigation of alerts, the vaccination of contacts, and the prevention and control activities. Thus, a significant upsurge of cases in health areas of Katwa and Butembo in the coming days is expected. The minister met with members of the sub-coordination and field teams to reassure them of the full support of the Ministry of Health.
- With the mayor of the city and the coordinator of the Butembo sub-coordination, the minister visited the sites of the 2 burned ETCs. The minister emphasized to the mayor of Butembo that it will be impossible to control the epidemic in the city until the security of the response team is assured.

Vaccination
-------
Since the beginning of vaccination on 8 Aug 2018, 84 361 people have been vaccinated [total numbers of people vaccinated in North Kivu, Ituri, Tshopo, and Haut-Uele provinces can be seen at the source URL above].

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Mary Marshall

- Wed 27 Feb 2019. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=693337893b

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 26 Feb 2019:
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 879, of which 814 are confirmed and 65 are probable. In total, there have been 553 deaths (488 of confirmed and 65 of probable cases).
- 229 suspected cases under investigation;
- 4 new confirmed cases, including 3 in Katwa and 1 in Butembo;
- 2 new deaths of confirmed cases, including 1 in Katwa and 1 in Butembo (all community deaths).



News of the response
Attack on Butembo Ebola treatment center
----------------------------------------
- On the evening of Wed 27 Feb 2019, unidentified gunmen attacked the Butembo ETC co-managed by Médecins Sans Frontières and the Ministry of Health. This attack took place only 3 days after the arson attack of the Katwa ETC, the neighboring health zone.
- At the time of the attack, 38 suspected patients and 12 confirmed patients were being treated at the ETC. Of the suspected patients, 32 fled. And among the confirmed cases, 8 were found in their single rooms. Research is under way to find the 4 confirmed ill fugitives. All the patients found, as well as the medical staff, are safe and unharmed. The patients were temporarily transferred to the Butembo transit center operated by Alima [Alliance for International Medical Action].

Workshop on the implementation of the 3rd strategic response plan (SRP)
-----------------------------------------------------------------
- On Tue 26 Feb 2019, the minister of health, Dr Oly Ilunga Kalenga, opened in Goma the workshop on the implementation of the 3rd strategic response plan (SRP 3) for the Ebola epidemic in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri. This workshop brought together all the national and international actors of the response, including all the health authorities of the different health zones of the region.

The purpose of the 2-day workshop was to explain the SRP 3 to all local health authorities, senior staff of strategic coordination and sub-coordination, as well as to give them ownership of the plan to ensure better implementation.
This new plan focuses on 3 important areas:
1. The anchoring of the response in the local health system: The leadership and the expertise of the response belong to the specialized teams, while the optimization of the functioning of the health system is the responsibility of the actors of the local health system (Provincial Division of Health, Health Zone, and Health Area).
2. The establishment of an information management system: The information management mechanism has been strengthened to improve data collection and analysis at all levels.
3. The importance of accountability: An important addition in SRP 3 is the accountability framework for each stakeholder involved in the response, both local providers and international partners. This accountability framework clearly identifies the roles and responsibilities of each organization in the response to assess their performance on the ground.

Vaccination
-----------
Since the beginning of vaccination on 8 Aug 2018, 84 094 persons have been vaccinated.

--
